00:35:57.618 --> 00:35:59.082
[END VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:35:59.082 --> 00:36:00.735
GARY KUNATH: Puts things
in perspective.

00:36:00.735 --> 00:36:02.460
In fact, it was interesting.

00:36:02.460 --> 00:36:05.290
Steve Jobs said remembering that
you will eventually die

00:36:05.290 --> 00:36:07.860
is the most important tool
you'll ever have to make those

00:36:07.860 --> 00:36:09.420
big decisions in life.

00:36:09.420 --> 00:36:12.910
All fear of failure, pride,
and enormity of risk, fall

00:36:12.910 --> 00:36:15.270
away in the face of death.

00:36:15.270 --> 00:36:18.576
The things I used to think
were such big deals, they

00:36:18.576 --> 00:36:20.490
weren't big deals.

00:36:20.490 --> 00:36:23.660
When I walk through a children's
cancer ward, I'm

00:36:23.660 --> 00:36:28.240
ashamed of what I thought
was a big deal or

00:36:28.240 --> 00:36:30.180
what bothered me.

00:36:30.180 --> 00:36:33.765
My son, who's your age, works
in the medical field.

00:36:33.765 --> 00:36:36.140
He's in surgeries.

00:36:36.140 --> 00:36:38.630
He had--

00:36:38.630 --> 00:36:40.270
he was in a surgery.

00:36:40.270 --> 00:36:44.590
And it was a simple
bowel re-section.

00:36:44.590 --> 00:36:47.930
I don't know how
they are but--

00:36:47.930 --> 00:36:50.310
and earlier in the week, he
had called me in sales.

00:36:50.310 --> 00:36:54.670
He goes, Dad, I'm really trying
to figure out how to

00:36:54.670 --> 00:36:57.640
make my sales quota, how to
make my sales numbers.

00:36:57.640 --> 00:36:59.300
I used to run a sales
training company.

00:36:59.300 --> 00:37:03.825
So that was an obvious area
that I knew about, which I

00:37:03.825 --> 00:37:04.460
also though was funny.

00:37:04.460 --> 00:37:06.470
Because when we lived at home,
he wasn't worried about making

00:37:06.470 --> 00:37:07.700
anything, including his bed.

00:37:07.700 --> 00:37:09.510
So I thought this was
really a very unique

00:37:09.510 --> 00:37:10.500
conversation for him.

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:12.800
Now he's worried about
making something.

00:37:12.800 --> 00:37:14.500
And he was really upset by it.

00:37:14.500 --> 00:37:15.320
And [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:15.320 --> 00:37:15.880
hindsight.

00:37:15.880 --> 00:37:16.980
I'm not saying it
was unimportant.

00:37:16.980 --> 00:37:18.902
I'm not saying it
was unimportant.

00:37:18.902 --> 00:37:23.110
But don't lose sleep over it.

00:37:23.110 --> 00:37:25.170
It's not that important.

00:37:25.170 --> 00:37:26.250
Of course, I can't tell him.

00:37:26.250 --> 00:37:29.650
Some things you just have to
experience before you get it.

00:37:29.650 --> 00:37:34.900
I can tell you, but it won't
register until you live it.

00:37:34.900 --> 00:37:36.200
And so we talked about that.

00:37:36.200 --> 00:37:38.260
We agreed we talk at the
end of the week.

00:37:38.260 --> 00:37:39.600
And the end of the week came.

00:37:39.600 --> 00:37:42.980
And I sensed there was a
difference in his voice.

00:37:42.980 --> 00:37:45.250
And I said, what's--

00:37:45.250 --> 00:37:46.960
tell me about what
happened today?

00:37:46.960 --> 00:37:48.520
What was your day like?

00:37:48.520 --> 00:37:51.760
He said we came out of
surgery today, Dad.

00:37:51.760 --> 00:37:54.160
He goes, there was
a guy in there.

00:37:54.160 --> 00:37:56.030
He's 32 years old.

00:37:56.030 --> 00:37:58.250
He was in for a simple
operation, should have a been

00:37:58.250 --> 00:37:59.560
boom, in and out.

00:37:59.560 --> 00:38:01.360
They opened him up.

00:38:01.360 --> 00:38:03.556
He was covered with cancer.

00:38:03.556 --> 00:38:08.610
He said, Dad, his wife is
in the waiting room.

00:38:08.610 --> 00:38:10.670
She had two little kids.

00:38:10.670 --> 00:38:13.170
She doesn't know that
her husband has a

00:38:13.170 --> 00:38:15.410
month, maybe less.

00:38:15.410 --> 00:38:18.470
And he doesn't know either.

00:38:18.470 --> 00:38:20.725
And he goes, Dad, I have
two little kids.

00:38:20.725 --> 00:38:23.611
That guy's my age.

00:38:23.611 --> 00:38:26.280
And I said, well, what
you learn from that?

00:38:26.280 --> 00:38:28.660
He goes maybe my sales
objectives

00:38:28.660 --> 00:38:31.570
aren't that big a deal.

00:38:31.570 --> 00:38:35.000
And again, I'm not saying
work is unimportant.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:38.940
But I'm saying the power of
perspective will save you.

00:38:38.940 --> 00:38:40.180
It saved me.

00:38:40.180 --> 00:38:42.380
The things I thought
had to be done.

00:38:42.380 --> 00:38:45.220
They didn't have to be done.

00:38:45.220 --> 00:38:47.250
They could have waited a day.

00:38:47.250 --> 00:38:49.010
I didn't have to
miss a birthday

00:38:49.010 --> 00:38:50.280
party to do those things.

00:38:50.280 --> 00:38:52.950
Are you kidding me?

00:38:52.950 --> 00:38:54.640
Never again.

00:38:54.640 --> 00:38:55.890
Never again.

00:38:59.780 --> 00:39:02.130
Just to give you some
perspective, this is an

00:39:02.130 --> 00:39:04.490
interesting calculation.

00:39:04.490 --> 00:39:06.260
Because I know you're young,
think you're bullet proof,

00:39:06.260 --> 00:39:08.190
think you're going
to live forever.

00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:10.970
Think you got an inordinate
amount of Saturdays left.

00:39:10.970 --> 00:39:12.520
Check this out.

00:39:12.520 --> 00:39:18.400
Multiply your age by 365,
subtract that from 27,375,

00:39:18.400 --> 00:39:24.330
which is on average the days
in a lifespan of 75 years.

00:39:24.330 --> 00:39:26.460
And what you get is the number
of days you have

00:39:26.460 --> 00:39:29.730
left to wake up.

00:39:29.730 --> 00:39:33.430
Now, since I'm older
then you--

00:39:33.430 --> 00:39:34.660
see here's how you know--

00:39:34.660 --> 00:39:38.310
here's how I knew I was
getting older--

00:39:38.310 --> 00:39:40.750
when I went into a music store
and everything I like is $1.

00:39:40.750 --> 00:39:43.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:43.120 --> 00:39:45.080
GARY KUNATH: And I also know I'm
getting older, when I call

00:39:45.080 --> 00:39:45.760
it a music store.

00:39:45.760 --> 00:39:47.880
That's another way I know
I'm getting older.

00:39:47.880 --> 00:39:50.280
But--

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:51.860
50 years old.

00:39:51.860 --> 00:39:52.940
Here's the math.

00:39:52.940 --> 00:39:54.130
I've broke it down.

00:39:54.130 --> 00:39:57.240
That's 1,300 Saturdays.

00:39:57.240 --> 00:39:59.420
When you think about it
like that, you don't

00:39:59.420 --> 00:40:02.560
want to blow a Saturday.

00:40:02.560 --> 00:40:03.560
And let me tell you something.

00:40:03.560 --> 00:40:07.870
That's if you make 75.

00:40:07.870 --> 00:40:09.120
You may not.

00:40:11.560 --> 00:40:13.800
One of the businesses that I'm
in is I own professional

00:40:13.800 --> 00:40:14.795
baseball teams.

00:40:14.795 --> 00:40:16.890
I don't know if you saw that
in the bio, but I do.

00:40:19.590 --> 00:40:21.730
We had opening day at one
of my teams in Brockton,

00:40:21.730 --> 00:40:24.450
Massachusetts, the
Brockton Rocks.

00:40:24.450 --> 00:40:28.290
And in the office, at the end
of the game, our mascot--

00:40:28.290 --> 00:40:29.830
We had a kangaroo
for a mascot.

00:40:29.830 --> 00:40:30.830
Don 't ask me why.

00:40:30.830 --> 00:40:33.100
Maybe we got a cheap deal
on a kangaroo outfit.

00:40:33.100 --> 00:40:35.496
I'm not sure why we have a
kangaroo and what that has to

00:40:35.496 --> 00:40:35.960
do with rocks.

00:40:35.960 --> 00:40:37.280
But anyway--

00:40:37.280 --> 00:40:37.950
So he comes out.

00:40:37.950 --> 00:40:40.850
And he's got a Syracuse
University t-shirt on.

00:40:40.850 --> 00:40:41.980
And I hadn't met him yet.

00:40:41.980 --> 00:40:42.910
And so I go, whoa, whoa, whoa.

00:40:42.910 --> 00:40:44.010
Get over here.

00:40:44.010 --> 00:40:45.500
I said, what's the deal
the Syracuse?

00:40:45.500 --> 00:40:46.650
He goes, well, I went
to Syracuse.

00:40:46.650 --> 00:40:48.570
I go, I went to Syracuse.

00:40:48.570 --> 00:40:50.190
He goes, well, I was the
mascot at Syracuse.

00:40:50.190 --> 00:40:51.080
He goes, I was the orange.

00:40:51.080 --> 00:40:52.160
He goes I was Otto the Orange.

00:40:52.160 --> 00:40:54.620
I go, I love Otto the Orange.

00:40:54.620 --> 00:40:56.430
So we had a great, great time.

00:40:56.430 --> 00:40:58.060
This kid was 26 years old.

00:40:58.060 --> 00:40:59.340
And we had the best time.

00:40:59.340 --> 00:41:00.740
What a delightful guy.

00:41:00.740 --> 00:41:03.270
We had a wild time.

00:41:03.270 --> 00:41:04.050
And we took a picture.

00:41:04.050 --> 00:41:06.990
I was so enamored with this guy,
we took a picture of he

00:41:06.990 --> 00:41:10.130
and I in the front office.

00:41:10.130 --> 00:41:14.760
Seven months later, he
died of leukemia--

00:41:14.760 --> 00:41:16.480
26 years old.

00:41:16.480 --> 00:41:18.480
He didn't know we had it.

00:41:18.480 --> 00:41:19.840
I didn't know he had it.

00:41:19.840 --> 00:41:22.780
His parents didn't
know he had it.

00:41:22.780 --> 00:41:25.260
Gone.

00:41:25.260 --> 00:41:26.510
26 years old.

00:41:31.220 --> 00:41:35.070
I keep . that picture in my
home for two reasons.

00:41:35.070 --> 00:41:37.620
One, I never want to
forget this kid.

00:41:37.620 --> 00:41:40.270
Because he was such a
vibrant life force.

00:41:40.270 --> 00:41:47.093
And two, I never want
to forget that can

00:41:47.093 --> 00:41:49.090
go away like this.

00:41:49.090 --> 00:41:51.150
It could be all gone in a day.

00:41:51.150 --> 00:41:53.970
You're life can change
in a second.

00:41:53.970 --> 00:41:58.520
And I don't want miss
one second of life.

00:42:04.290 --> 00:42:05.310
Top five regrets of the dying.

00:42:05.310 --> 00:42:09.440
This was compiled by 2000
hospice nurses.

00:42:09.440 --> 00:42:11.850
Here's what the dying said.

00:42:11.850 --> 00:42:15.030
I wished I had courage to live a
life true to myself, not the

00:42:15.030 --> 00:42:17.020
life expected of me.

00:42:17.020 --> 00:42:20.050
I wished I hadn't
worked so hard.

00:42:20.050 --> 00:42:23.870
I wished I had the courage to
express my true feelings.

00:42:23.870 --> 00:42:26.080
I wished I had stayed in
touch with my friends.

00:42:26.080 --> 00:42:28.150
And this last one kills
me, I wished I

00:42:28.150 --> 00:42:31.310
let myself be happier.

00:42:31.310 --> 00:42:35.030
Top five of people dying.

00:42:35.030 --> 00:42:37.820
They can't have I do over.

00:42:42.020 --> 00:42:42.610
Why?

00:42:42.610 --> 00:42:46.200
Why must it be then when this
comes to your mind?

00:42:46.200 --> 00:42:49.080
That's what made me on a mission
to say, don't let that

00:42:49.080 --> 00:42:50.330
happen to you.

00:42:54.810 --> 00:42:55.910
Good goes around--

00:42:55.910 --> 00:42:57.340
another point of life.

00:42:57.340 --> 00:42:59.080
I'm a big believer.

00:42:59.080 --> 00:43:02.150
Being a better giver makes you
better getter, as long as you

00:43:02.150 --> 00:43:05.250
don't give to get.

00:43:05.250 --> 00:43:07.370
I believe that with
all my heart.

00:43:07.370 --> 00:43:08.865
I've experienced that.

00:43:12.370 --> 00:43:16.770
One of my businesses now is
highly philanthropic, where

00:43:16.770 --> 00:43:19.140
every 10 years our goal is to
give a billion dollars to

00:43:19.140 --> 00:43:20.390
cause related charities.

00:43:23.840 --> 00:43:26.210
Being a better giver makes you
a better getter, as long as

00:43:26.210 --> 00:43:27.630
you don't give to get.

00:43:27.630 --> 00:43:30.840
Here's how I know
that to be true.

00:43:30.840 --> 00:43:33.090
When I was first starting my
first business, The Summit

00:43:33.090 --> 00:43:36.760
Group, which was the
sales training.

00:43:36.760 --> 00:43:38.590
And I was looking for
that big hat.

00:43:38.590 --> 00:43:41.550
In my neighborhood, I would
run to blow off the steam.

00:43:41.550 --> 00:43:43.040
And I would pass this woman.

00:43:43.040 --> 00:43:43.800
And we'd just say, hi.

00:43:43.800 --> 00:43:44.580
Hi.

00:43:44.580 --> 00:43:46.850
And go about our business.

00:43:46.850 --> 00:43:49.070
And then one day, I got
knock on my door.

00:43:49.070 --> 00:43:49.640
And I opened the door.

00:43:49.640 --> 00:43:50.940
And it was her.

00:43:50.940 --> 00:43:54.000
And she was just as surprised to
see that I lived there as I

00:43:54.000 --> 00:43:56.550
was to see that she's
knocking on my door.

00:43:56.550 --> 00:43:58.960
And I go, what's up?

00:43:58.960 --> 00:44:03.630
She goes, well, I'm
collecting for my

00:44:03.630 --> 00:44:05.970
neighbor, whose son has--

00:44:05.970 --> 00:44:06.630
he's eight years old.

00:44:06.630 --> 00:44:08.140
He has leukemia.

00:44:08.140 --> 00:44:10.440
And they're taking him for
treatment at Boston.

00:44:10.440 --> 00:44:13.300
And they don't have enough money
for them to stay with

00:44:13.300 --> 00:44:15.220
their son during this
treatment period.

00:44:15.220 --> 00:44:17.910
So I'm running to raise
money in donations.

00:44:17.910 --> 00:44:19.570
And I'm telling you.

00:44:19.570 --> 00:44:21.210
I don't know what
made me do this.

00:44:21.210 --> 00:44:24.380
To this day, I don't know
what made me do this.

00:44:24.380 --> 00:44:26.270
I just looked at her,
and I said, well,

00:44:26.270 --> 00:44:28.280
how much do you need?

00:44:28.280 --> 00:44:29.780
And she told me.

00:44:29.780 --> 00:44:32.180
And I said, wait here.

00:44:32.180 --> 00:44:34.850
And I went in and I came back
with a check for the entire

00:44:34.850 --> 00:44:38.530
amount, handed it to her.

00:44:38.530 --> 00:44:41.410
And I got a call from the kid's
parents that night.

00:44:41.410 --> 00:44:42.870
It was a call I'll never
forget-- crying.

00:44:42.870 --> 00:44:44.500
They couldn't believe
a stranger had

00:44:44.500 --> 00:44:47.840
done this for them.

00:44:47.840 --> 00:44:49.560
It was a call I'll
never forget.

00:44:49.560 --> 00:44:55.670
But the real part of the story
that is amazing to me is, as

00:44:55.670 --> 00:44:59.330
I'm trying to build this
business, I need this one big

00:44:59.330 --> 00:45:01.290
hit to get going.

00:45:01.290 --> 00:45:06.470
About 30 maybe 45 days
later, I get a call.

00:45:06.470 --> 00:45:08.030
It's from the director of
training at Southern

00:45:08.030 --> 00:45:10.800
California Edison.

00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:13.630
And she's talking about
sales training.

00:45:13.630 --> 00:45:17.490
So we had a conversation for 45
minutes on sales training.

00:45:17.490 --> 00:45:21.030
At the end of the conversation,
she goes so this

00:45:21.030 --> 00:45:23.160
is the ABC Company, right?

00:45:23.160 --> 00:45:27.180
And I go, no, this is
the Summit Group.

00:45:27.180 --> 00:45:30.270
So goes, I was calling
ABC Company.

00:45:30.270 --> 00:45:32.400
I go, well--

00:45:32.400 --> 00:45:33.650
So now I'm thinking, ugh.

00:45:35.220 --> 00:45:38.430
She goes, I must have dialed
the wrong number.

00:45:38.430 --> 00:45:39.330
She goes, but it
doesn't matter.

00:45:39.330 --> 00:45:40.810
Because, you know what?

00:45:40.810 --> 00:45:43.390
What you talked about,
I really liked.

00:45:43.390 --> 00:45:46.130
That turned into a seven
figure contract for me.

00:45:46.130 --> 00:45:48.300
That launched my business
at Summit Group.

00:45:48.300 --> 00:45:51.250
You can't tell me those
things aren't related.

00:45:51.250 --> 00:45:52.550
What are the odds of that?

00:45:52.550 --> 00:45:54.340
What are the odds of her not
even saying, is this the

00:45:54.340 --> 00:45:56.150
Summit Group up front
in our conversation?

00:45:56.150 --> 00:45:57.910
Because if she had said,
that would have said--

00:45:57.910 --> 00:46:00.040
or is this ABC company,
I'd have said, no.

00:46:00.040 --> 00:46:00.180
That'd have been it.

00:46:00.180 --> 00:46:02.720
She'd have hung up
and redialed.

00:46:02.720 --> 00:46:05.030
Where are the odds of that?

00:46:05.030 --> 00:46:06.990
Good does go around.

00:46:06.990 --> 00:46:08.460
In fact, I'd don't know
if you saw this.

00:46:08.460 --> 00:46:13.020
This was just recent, where a
woman was shopping and had a

00:46:13.020 --> 00:46:15.980
bumper sticker saluting her
husband, who was over in

00:46:15.980 --> 00:46:17.490
Afghanistan serving.

00:46:17.490 --> 00:46:19.490
She came back to her car.

00:46:19.490 --> 00:46:21.860
This a note was taped
to her windshield

00:46:21.860 --> 00:46:23.540
along with 40 dollars.

00:46:23.540 --> 00:46:25.750
And it said, I noticed
the sticker on the

00:46:25.750 --> 00:46:27.050
back of your car.

00:46:27.050 --> 00:46:29.380
Take your hero out to dinner
when he comes home.

00:46:29.380 --> 00:46:32.540
Thank you both for serving,
him deployed and you for

00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:35.900
waiting, United States
veteran, God bless.

00:46:35.900 --> 00:46:39.270
That had like two million
hits in about six hours.

00:46:39.270 --> 00:46:41.300
That's how good goes around.

00:46:41.300 --> 00:46:43.660
I'm a big believer in that.

00:46:43.660 --> 00:46:44.910
Practicing the art
of savoring--

00:46:49.090 --> 00:46:54.060
one of the things that
I do every day is I

00:46:54.060 --> 00:46:56.755
take time to read.

00:46:59.680 --> 00:47:01.560
I'll look at the stars.

00:47:01.560 --> 00:47:03.090
I'll just sit and look
at the stars.

00:47:03.090 --> 00:47:04.420
I'll watch the birds.

