00:55:42.760 --> 00:55:44.010
Relationship Refinement--

00:55:44.010 --> 00:55:46.440
couple last things here.

00:55:46.440 --> 00:55:48.510
What I found to be very helpful
in my life, especially

00:55:48.510 --> 00:55:51.370
as I get older, I don't have
time for people who waste my

00:55:51.370 --> 00:55:55.060
time, people who suck the
life force out of me.

00:55:55.060 --> 00:55:56.410
There are energy gainers.

00:55:56.410 --> 00:56:00.330
There are energy drainers,
takers, and 1%ers.

00:56:00.330 --> 00:56:03.320
Takers, unfortunately,
there's a lot of.

00:56:03.320 --> 00:56:06.400
1%ers are people care as much if
not more about you as they

00:56:06.400 --> 00:56:07.760
do themselves.

00:56:07.760 --> 00:56:10.050
Energy gainers, I like
hanging around.

00:56:10.050 --> 00:56:11.860
They make me feel better
about myself.

00:56:11.860 --> 00:56:15.570
Energy drainers are people that
just suck the life force

00:56:15.570 --> 00:56:16.100
out of you.

00:56:16.100 --> 00:56:19.490
You feel worse when they've
been around you.

00:56:19.490 --> 00:56:22.100
And I try to identify
frenemies early.

00:56:22.100 --> 00:56:23.170
I try to figure out who--

00:56:23.170 --> 00:56:25.000
I don't want to waste my time.

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:27.980
So there's four things I look at
when I decide who I'm going

00:56:27.980 --> 00:56:29.760
to hang around, to try to
read the tea leaves.

00:56:29.760 --> 00:56:31.050
I look at four things.

00:56:31.050 --> 00:56:35.340
One, I try to observe how people
spend their money.

00:56:35.340 --> 00:56:37.930
It tells me something
about them.

00:56:37.930 --> 00:56:39.230
People vote with their money.

00:56:39.230 --> 00:56:42.120
Do they buy things
or experiences?

00:56:42.120 --> 00:56:44.430
Are they impulsive
or thoughtful?

00:56:44.430 --> 00:56:48.070
Are they buying in abundance or
scarcity kind of mentality?

00:56:48.070 --> 00:56:49.320
Then I look at their friends--

00:56:49.320 --> 00:56:53.170
there's an old Sicilian saying,
show me who you hang

00:56:53.170 --> 00:56:56.060
around and I will show
you who you are.

00:56:56.060 --> 00:56:57.730
That tells me what kind of
friendships they have--

00:56:57.730 --> 00:56:59.460
transactional or unconditional,
short

00:56:59.460 --> 00:57:00.950
term or long term.

00:57:00.950 --> 00:57:02.810
Then I look at how they
speak of themselves.

00:57:02.810 --> 00:57:04.240
That tells me at ton.

00:57:04.240 --> 00:57:05.240
What's their operating model?

00:57:05.240 --> 00:57:05.655
Are they humble?

00:57:05.655 --> 00:57:06.730
Or are they boastful?

00:57:06.730 --> 00:57:07.740
Do hold a grudge?

00:57:07.740 --> 00:57:08.560
Or are they forgiving?

00:57:08.560 --> 00:57:10.310
Do they give credit
or take credit?

00:57:10.310 --> 00:57:13.820
What's the balance of listening
versus talking?

00:57:13.820 --> 00:57:14.890
We used to have a neighbor.

00:57:14.890 --> 00:57:15.800
My father never liked her.

00:57:15.800 --> 00:57:19.690
He goes, she has two gears,
talking and waiting to talk.

00:57:19.690 --> 00:57:22.090
And so I says, that's a
pretty good one, dad.

00:57:22.090 --> 00:57:23.110
Anyway.

00:57:23.110 --> 00:57:25.440
And then the last thing I look
at is I observe how do they

00:57:25.440 --> 00:57:28.360
treat people and things
they don't need.

00:57:28.360 --> 00:57:30.490
How do they treat kids,
senior citizens,

00:57:30.490 --> 00:57:32.740
relatives, service people?

00:57:32.740 --> 00:57:33.380
How do they do that?

00:57:33.380 --> 00:57:35.740
I was over at one acquaintance's
house, and

00:57:35.740 --> 00:57:38.850
their 12-year-old was acting up,
was so rude at the table.

00:57:38.850 --> 00:57:39.600
I couldn't believe it.

00:57:39.600 --> 00:57:41.095
And the mother thought she
needed to address it.

00:57:41.095 --> 00:57:42.360
She goes, oh--

00:57:42.360 --> 00:57:43.380
he even swore at table.

00:57:43.380 --> 00:57:45.670
She goes, oh, that's
our little Timmy.

00:57:45.670 --> 00:57:46.940
He's very opinionated.

00:57:46.940 --> 00:57:48.430
I go, little Timmy's
is going to jail.

00:57:48.430 --> 00:57:49.600
[LAUGHTER]

00:57:49.600 --> 00:57:50.740
GARY KUNATH: You better
fix him before he

00:57:50.740 --> 00:57:53.490
robs me in 10 years.

00:57:53.490 --> 00:57:58.560
So all I have to say is this--

00:57:58.560 --> 00:58:01.310
you get what you
accept in life.

00:58:01.310 --> 00:58:04.640
And to me, happiness is
the ultimate currency.

00:58:04.640 --> 00:58:07.170
Those who wish to sing
always find a song.

00:58:07.170 --> 00:58:09.540
The two most important days in
your life are the day you are

00:58:09.540 --> 00:58:12.680
born and the day you
discover why.

00:58:12.680 --> 00:58:15.480
And life is like riding a
10-speed bike, most of us have

00:58:15.480 --> 00:58:16.990
gears we've never used.

00:58:16.990 --> 00:58:19.070
And the this next one came
directly from Willie Nelson.

00:58:19.070 --> 00:58:20.200
He told me this.

00:58:20.200 --> 00:58:22.610
Doesn't matter how heavy
something is, what matters is

00:58:22.610 --> 00:58:23.550
how long you have to hold.

00:58:23.550 --> 00:58:25.160
It I don't know what he meant.

00:58:25.160 --> 00:58:26.290
It may have been a doobie.

00:58:26.290 --> 00:58:28.990
I'm not sure what he was
thinking about there.

00:58:28.990 --> 00:58:31.240
Things that surprise me
most about people.

00:58:31.240 --> 00:58:32.500
We get bored with childhood.

00:58:32.500 --> 00:58:34.110
We rush to grow up.

00:58:34.110 --> 00:58:36.740
And then we long to become
children again.

00:58:36.740 --> 00:58:39.100
We lose our health to
try to make money.

00:58:39.100 --> 00:58:42.240
And then we lose our money to
try to get back our health.

00:58:42.240 --> 00:58:44.490
We live as it will never die.

00:58:44.490 --> 00:58:46.830
And we die as though
we've never lived.

00:58:46.830 --> 00:58:49.040
And we don't understand that a
rich person is not the one who

00:58:49.040 --> 00:58:53.830
makes the most, but it's the
one who needs the least.

00:58:53.830 --> 00:58:56.120
The best things in life
are not things.

00:58:56.120 --> 00:58:58.290
And what I really want you to
understand is, don't ever

00:58:58.290 --> 00:59:01.550
forget why it is you
do what you do.

00:59:01.550 --> 00:59:02.770
I know you work hard.

00:59:02.770 --> 00:59:03.230
You do.

00:59:03.230 --> 00:59:05.140
I know.

00:59:05.140 --> 00:59:08.250
But don't forget why
you work hard.

00:59:08.250 --> 00:59:13.380
The best definition, to me,
success is applause at home.

00:59:13.380 --> 00:59:14.630
And I'll end with this--

00:59:19.420 --> 00:59:22.050
the eulogy.

00:59:22.050 --> 00:59:26.060
I saw a man who stood to speak
at the funeral of a friend.

00:59:26.060 --> 00:59:28.190
He referred to the dates on
the tombstone from the

00:59:28.190 --> 00:59:29.910
beginning to the end.

00:59:29.910 --> 00:59:31.650
He noted the first date
was her birth.

00:59:31.650 --> 00:59:33.750
And the second was
when she passed.

00:59:33.750 --> 00:59:35.390
He said, we never truly
know just how

00:59:35.390 --> 00:59:37.340
long lives might last.

00:59:37.340 --> 00:59:40.360
Then he paused a bit, trying
to fight back his tears.

00:59:40.360 --> 00:59:43.190
And then he said, what truly
matters, though, is the dash

00:59:43.190 --> 00:59:44.680
between those years.

00:59:44.680 --> 00:59:46.700
For that dash represents
all the time we

00:59:46.700 --> 00:59:48.260
spent alive on earth.

00:59:48.260 --> 00:59:50.710
And only those who've loved you
can know what that little

00:59:50.710 --> 00:59:52.020
line is worth.

00:59:52.020 --> 00:59:54.940
Then he said, it matters not how
much we own, the cars, the

00:59:54.940 --> 00:59:56.090
house, the cash.

00:59:56.090 --> 00:59:59.930
What matters most is how we live
and how we love and how

00:59:59.930 --> 01:00:01.780
we spend that dash.

01:00:01.780 --> 01:00:04.450
So think about this long and
hard, are the things you'd

01:00:04.450 --> 01:00:05.840
like to change.

01:00:05.840 --> 01:00:08.360
For you never know how much time
is left that can still be

01:00:08.360 --> 01:00:09.760
rearranged.

01:00:09.760 --> 01:00:11.590
So when your eulogy is read.

01:00:11.590 --> 01:00:14.860
And your life's actions to
rehash, would you be proud of

01:00:14.860 --> 01:00:18.880
the things they say about
how you spend your dash.

01:00:18.880 --> 01:00:19.610
Thank you very much.

01:00:19.610 --> 01:00:20.810
Let me turn it over to Ben.

01:00:20.810 --> 01:00:22.300
You guys have been great
to hang with me.

01:00:22.300 --> 01:00:23.580
I know you guys-- you're
running and

01:00:23.580 --> 01:00:24.500
gunning all the time.

01:00:24.500 --> 01:00:24.800
But thank you.

01:00:24.800 --> 01:00:30.137
[APPLAUSE]

